Navy Flight, Maneuvers, San Diego-Pearl Harbor
Twelve Navy PBY patrol bombers of Patrol
Six took off from the harbor at San Diego at 6:05
Squadron 150
a.m., January 28, for Pearl Harbor. They flew the
2,631 miles in 21 hours and 48 minutes, meaning that
they arrived and landed in Hawaii before dawn. These
large seaplanes, under the command of Lt. Cmdr.
William M. McDade, carried a crew of 80 and flew
approximately 300 covers. Most of the covers are
cancelled "Aircraft Base Force, U.S. Fleet, San
Diego, Calif., Jan. 28, 1937" although a few are
cancelled on January 27. All covers are backstamped
"Fleet Air Base, Pearl Harbor, T.H., Jan. 29, 1937".
This marked the first flight to Hawaii from a U.S.
mainland point other than San Francisco. It also
marked the first of many Navy flights between San
Diego and Pearl Harbor that were to occur before
World War II. On almost all of these Navy flights
souvenir covers were flown.
(AAMC: TO 1276)

Green, EC [illegible], Hank [illegible].a. envelopeb. insert: photocopied information sheet with additional information from donor on "Navy Flight, Maneuvers, San Diego-Pearl Harbor."
